I have added multiple images of in situ fruiting bodies fruiting within a few feet of Chalciporus piperatus to show association(possible mycelial parasitization). This small strip of grass where the root networks of the Doug fir and western hemlock meet has quite the fungal diversity, symbioses, parasitization and mutually benefitting species occurring side by side throughout the season(Gompidius glutinosus and G. subroseus w/Suillus spp., Amanita muscaria subsp. flavivolvata w/Chalciporus and Boletus edulis var. grandedulis, Russula spp. with Hypomyces lactifluorum, Inocybe spp. and A. pachycolea), all within approximately a 100ft transect. I have witnessed and monitored associations such as these in forested locations for years(they are just harder to see most times due to understory cover). This spot is a perfect microcosm(or should I say Myco-cosm) to witness these associations on open, grassy and easily visible ground. It is always a nice idea to look closely at nearby flushing species and note them in a journal, as, most often, one will come across the same associations between mycorrhizal hosts/sympathetic/parasitic species together in multiple, varying habitats, elevations and occurrence times throughout the year. I had planned to monitor the growth of flushes here and take multiple time lapse images(as with last season) for a few weeks to show development and stages of fruiting, but alas, local children and dogs got to the patch before I could add any updates. Feeling lucky, either way, to have such a fungally diverse spot so close to home. We’ll see what comes up next as temps continue to drop and heavy rains increase.

results.notes:
[Tullis-Krstic foray]

Growing on decaying sticks and branches, on the ground. No odor, ‘fungal’ taste. Stems rather tough.

Basidia 4-spored, 40+3.5 × 7. Spores 8-11 × 4-6.5, apparently hyaline and inamyloid (possibly weakly amyloid). Cheilocystidia abundant, 40-70 × 6-9. Pleurocystidia either absent, or like cheilos (didn’t check carefully). Pileipellis a cutis, with tightly packed clamped hyphae, 3-5 microns wide. Hyphae of the stipitipellis often curved, terminal cells simple (cylindrical).

All tissues clamped, no reactions in Melzer’s.
